data.content:
Yes! Modern MSTest (v3.4+) supports **typed tuples** with `DynamicData`, eliminating the `object[]` indirection:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What's better:**
- Compile-time type safety — no risk of runtime cast failures
- Tuple element names serve as documentation
- Refactoring tools catch mismatches immediately

For simple constants, `[DataRow]` also works without a separate property:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

Use `DynamicData` with tuples when your test data involves non-constants (objects, computed values); use `[DataRow]` when all arguments are compile-time literals.
